specifics.specific:
- demonstrate and explain equivalent representations of a decimal number, using
concrete materials and drawings (e.g., use base ten materials to show that three
tenths [0.3] is equal to thirty hundredths [0.30]);

- estimate and measure the perimeter and area of regular and irregular polygons,
using a variety of tools (e.g., grid paper, geoboard, dynamic geometry software)
and strategies.

- collect and organize discrete or continuous primary data and secondary data and display the data in charts, tables, and graphs (including broken-line graphs) that have appropriate titles, labels (e.g., appropriate units marked on the axes), and scales that suit the range and distribution of the data
(e.g., to represent precipitation amounts ranging from 0 mm to 50 mm over the
school year, use a scale of 5 mm for each unit on the vertical axis and show months on the horizontal axis), using a variety of tools (e.g., graph paper, simple spreadsheets, dynamic statistical software);
